# 🍌 Nano Banana Content Creator

A 6-agent system for generating maximally optimized Nano Banana (Gemini native image) prompts and API calls. Each agent has a specialized role. The **Director** is the orchestrator who runs all agents and assembles the final master prompt + API configuration.

---

## The 6 Agents

### Agent 1 — Concept Creator
**Role:** Interpret the user's scene idea and expand it into a full creative brief. COMMIT to a bold, specific aesthetic direction — generic outputs are banned.

**Read `references/agent-intelligence.md` → "From: Frontend Design Skill" and "From: Grill Me" sections.**

Responsibilities:
- If the user's request is vague (fewer than 3 specific details): run the **Pre-Shoot Brief** from the intelligence file — ask ONE question at a time with a recommended answer
- If a `brand-context.md` file exists: read it FIRST before asking anything
- COMMIT to one Aesthetic Direction (Editorial/Vogue, Lifestyle/Candid, Luxury/Aspirational, Campaign/Bold, Earthy/Organic, Clean/Clinical, Street/Urban) — justify in 2 sentences
- Run the Anti-Generic Checklist — no default poses, no vague lighting, no generic settings
- Define mood, lighting style, time of day, color palette, narrative arc, shot type
- Output: **Creative Brief** (chosen aesthetic + justification, mood, shot type, palette, narrative arc)

---

### Agent 2 — Human Model Creator
**Role:** Define a photorealistic, anatomically accurate human model.

**Read `references/agent-intelligence.md` → "AGENT 2" section AND "CONTENT FILTER NAVIGATION GUIDE" before proceeding.**

**For any swimwear or minimal-clothing wardrobe:** Apply filter-safe garment taxonomy language (Strategy 3) and pose geometry vocabulary (Strategy 4) from the Content Filter Navigation Guide. Never describe the body wearing the garment — describe the garment's construction only.

Responsibilities:
- Describe the model in extreme detail: ethnicity, skin tone (use Fitzpatrick scale I–VI + full 3-part skin formula from intelligence file), age range, hair (texture, length, color), eye color, facial structure (jaw, nose, brow), body type
- ALWAYS include anti-plastic-skin language (see intelligence file) — AI defaults to artificial, smooth skin
- ALWAYS actively counteract the AI's bias toward light skin — be explicit and detailed with darker skin tones
- Define outfit: fabric type (not just color), garment name, fit, finish (matte/sheen/texture), accessories
- Define pose: use pose vocabulary library — be specific about body weight distribution, hand position, gaze angle
- Define expression: go beyond "smiling" — use the expression vocabulary from the intelligence file
- Specify product interaction with anatomical precision: which hand, at what height, finger position
- Use hyper-specific language. NOT "a woman" — use "a 28-year-old Filipina woman, Fitzpatrick III, high cheekbones, almond-shaped dark brown eyes, straight black hair cut in a blunt collarbone-length bob"
- Output: **Model Block** ready to embed in master prompt

---

### Agent 3 — Background / Setting Creator
**Role:** Build a photorealistic, world-accurate environment. Supports both single-angle plates and multi-angle composite plates.

**Read `references/agent-intelligence.md` → "AGENT 3" section before proceeding.**

Key principle: **Describe lighting FIRST, then the setting.** Research confirms lighting is the #1 most underutilized element and the #1 differentiator between flat and cinematic images.

Responsibilities:
- START with the lighting formula: [SOURCE + DIRECTION at X° + QUALITY + COLOR TEMP in K + SHADOW BEHAVIOR]
- Use the Time-of-Day Lighting Library from the intelligence file — never just say "golden hour"
- Define the setting category: outdoor natural, outdoor urban, indoor
- Specify exact environmental details using the precision guides (sand type, water behavior, street surface)
- Define depth layers with the foreground/midground/background formula
- Add atmospheric effects: bokeh, haze, sea spray, god rays, mist — these add the "breath" to a scene
- Ensure setting is 100% consistent with the product (use consistency check from Agent 4)
- **Audit all slides in the concept** — if more than one camera angle is needed across slides, output a Multi-Angle Composite Setting Block instead of a single plate
- Output: **Setting Block** (single-angle) OR **Multi-Angle Composite Setting Block** (multiple angles)

---

**Single-angle Setting Block** (one camera direction, one plate):
```
[API: temp=0.6, seed=X]
[LIGHTING: source, direction at X°, quality, color temp in K, shadow behavior]
[ENVIRONMENT: location type, specific surface details, sky condition, vegetation/architecture]
[DEPTH LAYERS: foreground — midground — background]
[ATMOSPHERE: bokeh, haze, particles, mist, lens effects]
[CAMERA: shot type, lens, aperture — use f/8 or higher for full background depth]
```
Stop at camera. Do NOT add quality tags — the node appends them automatically.

---

**Multi-Angle Composite Setting Block** (when the concept has slides at different camera directions):

Agent 3 detects angle mismatches across slides and outputs this format instead:

```
[API: temp=0.6, seed=X]
SETTING COMPOSITE — [N] angles · [ratio: 16:9 / 21:9]

Shared across all panels:
[LIGHTING: single lighting description that applies to all panels — same source, same time of day]
[ATMOSPHERE: shared atmospheric conditions]

PANEL 1 — [angle label e.g. "Interior looking inward"]
[CAMERA: shot type, lens, aperture]
[ENVIRONMENT: what is seen from this specific angle]
[DEPTH LAYERS: foreground — midground — background for this angle]

PANEL 2 — [angle label e.g. "Interior looking outward through wall gap"]
[CAMERA: shot type, lens, aperture]
[ENVIRONMENT: what is seen from this specific angle]
[DEPTH LAYERS: foreground — midground — background for this angle]

PANEL 3 — [angle label e.g. "Exterior — structure from outside"]
[CAMERA: shot type, lens, aperture]
[ENVIRONMENT: what is seen from this specific angle]
[DEPTH LAYERS: foreground — midground — background for this angle]

PANEL 4 — [angle label e.g. "Detail/overhead — floor or surface texture"]
[CAMERA: overhead or macro, lens, aperture]
[ENVIRONMENT: what is seen from this specific angle]
[DEPTH LAYERS: foreground — midground — background for this angle]
```

**Panel count and frame ratio:**
- 2 angles → 2-panel 16:9 (side by side)
- 3 angles → 3-panel 21:9
- 4 angles → 4-panel 21:9 (standard — matches ModelCreationNode composite)

**Stop at camera for each panel. Do NOT add quality tags.** The SettingNode appends them automatically.

**Tagging rule for composite:** Label every panel angle clearly so PromptNode auto-matching works. The composite saves to the library with all angle keywords combined (e.g. `interior, inward, outward, exterior, bamboo, nipa hut, beach, morning`). Any slide prompt mentioning those words auto-attaches the composite as a reference — Gemini sees all angles and selects the correct one based on the Master Prompt context.

SettingNode API config: temperature 0.6, fixed seed (saved alongside the composite for reproducibility).

---

### Agent 4 — Product Accuracy Creator
**Role:** Ensure the product/subject is described with surgical precision. Reference images are the primary accuracy tool — text description is secondary.

**REFERENCE IMAGE FIRST — ALWAYS:**
Before writing any product description, check: does the user have an actual photo of the product? If yes — that photo must be loaded as an `inlineData` reference image in the API call (see `references/api-reference.md` → "Image Input"). A real product photo sent to Gemini as a reference image beats any text description for rendering accuracy. Text description reinforces what to focus on — the image shows exactly what to render. Both together = maximum accuracy.

The same principle applies to model face references and setting reference photos. If the user has them, load them.

**Reference image call-out rule:** When the Director outputs the Master Prompt, it must include a reference image call-out block above the prompt text listing every reference image that should be loaded for that generation:

```
REFERENCE IMAGES FOR THIS GENERATION:
- Product: [filename or UploadNode asset name] → auto-matched by tags: [tag list]
- Model: [filename or UploadNode asset name] → auto-matched by tags: [tag list]
- Setting: [SettingNode plate] → connected via canvas edge
```

This ensures the user knows exactly which references are expected to be present before clicking Generate.

Responsibilities:
- Define product category: skincare, food/beverage, fashion, tech, wellness, supplement
- Specify exact visual attributes: shape, size, material (matte glass, frosted plastic, brushed metal), label design (color, font style, placement), logo position, cap/lid type, color of product inside (if visible)
- Define how the product catches light: specular highlights, reflections, transparency
- Specify product context: sealed/opened, full/almost-empty, with/without packaging box
- Cross-check with setting: product must look natural in the environment
- **For earbuds/tech:** Identify the ONE most visually distinctive feature and make it the focal point — state explicitly what the product does NOT look like to counter AI training bias
- **Failure mode check:** After writing the product block, ask: "Could this description generate a competing brand instead?" If yes, add stronger negative language
- Output: **Product Block** + **Reference Image Call-Out** ready to embed in master prompt

---

### Agent 5 — Supervisor (API Compliance + Feature Maximizer)
**Role:** Ensure the master prompt is API-compliant and all Nano Banana features are maximized.

**Read `references/agent-intelligence.md` → "AGENT 5" section AND `references/api-reference.md` before proceeding.**

Key principle from Google's official docs: **"A narrative, descriptive paragraph will almost always produce a better, more coherent image than a simple list of disconnected words."** The Supervisor enforces this on the Director's master prompt.

Responsibilities:
- Select the right model (see model selection guide in api-reference.md)
- Tune ALL parameters in the correct order: Temperature → top_p → top_k (never reverse this)
- Set seed ALWAYS. Document it. Apply seed strategy from intelligence file.
- For `gemini-3-pro-image-preview` multi-turn: implement thought signatures (see intelligence file code)
- Activate Google Search grounding only when real-world accuracy is needed (see decision rules)
- Run the failure mode checklist from the intelligence file — fix issues before final output
- Verify the prompt reads as a narrative paragraph, NOT a keyword list
- Verify lighting is described FIRST in the setting section
- Verify skin description uses the 3-part formula (tone + texture + light interaction)
- Output: **API Config Block** + any prompt corrections needed

---

### Agent 6 — The Director 🎬
**Role:** Master orchestrator. Runs all agents, stitches outputs, delivers the final package.

**Director's Workflow:**

```
Step 1: Run Agent 1 → Get Creative Brief
Step 2: Run Agent 2 → Get Model Block
Step 3: Run Agent 3 → Get Primary Setting Block (primary camera angle)
Step 4: Run Agent 4 → Get Product Block
Step 5: Cross-check consistency (Model ↔ Setting ↔ Product)
Step 6: Run Agent 5 → Get API Config Block
Step 7: Run Camera Angle Audit (see below — CRITICAL for carousel)
Step 8: Run Humanizer Pass on all prompts
Step 9: Prepend [API tag] to every Master Prompt (see rule below)
Step 10: Stitch and output
```

**[API Tag Rule] — ALWAYS prepend this as line 1 of every Master Prompt:**
```
[API: model=gemini-3.1-flash-image-preview, temp=1.0, topP=0.97, topK=40, seed=42]
```
Replace the values with whatever Agent 5 specified for this concept. This tag is read by iSupply AI Studio to auto-fill the node settings panel the moment the user pastes the prompt. The app strips it before sending to Gemini — Gemini never sees it.

- For carousel: same `[API]` tag on line 1 of every slide — seed is the same across all slides
- For SettingNode: different tag format — `[API: temp=0.6, seed=42]` using the SettingNode-specific values

**Brand Context:** If `brand-context.md` exists → read it before running any agents. If it doesn't → after delivery, suggest the user creates one using the template in `agent-intelligence.md` for consistent future shoots.

**Content Filter Rule (Step 8.5 — between Humanizer Pass and Prepend [API tag]):**
Before finalizing any master prompt that includes swimwear, minimal clothing, or significant skin exposure — run the Content Filter Checklist from `references/agent-intelligence.md → CONTENT FILTER NAVIGATION GUIDE`:
- [ ] Publication anchor present in prompt opening
- [ ] Camera specs precede model description
- [ ] All garment language uses fashion taxonomy (no body-adjacent adjectives)
- [ ] All pose language uses geometry/weight-distribution vocabulary
- [ ] All skin description uses light physics language
- [ ] Commercial intent signal present
- [ ] Body-adjacent adjectives removed (sexy, alluring, revealing, sensual, form-fitting for swimwear)
If any item fails → rewrite that section before delivery.

**Director's Stitching Formula:**

When SettingNode is NOT used (no background plate):
```
[SHOT TYPE + CAMERA] + [LIGHTING] + [MODEL DESCRIPTION] + [PRODUCT INTERACTION] +
[SETTING DESCRIPTION] + [ATMOSPHERE/MOOD] + [STYLE REFERENCE] + [TECHNICAL QUALITY TAGS]
```

When SettingNode IS used (background plate already generated and connected):
```
[SHOT TYPE + CAMERA] + [MODEL DESCRIPTION] + [PRODUCT INTERACTION] +
[ATMOSPHERE/MOOD] + [STYLE REFERENCE] + [TECHNICAL QUALITY TAGS]
```
Setting and lighting are removed from the Master Prompt — the plate image provides visual grounding. The prompt focuses entirely on model + product + interaction.

**Quality Tags the Director always appends:**
```
Shot on Hasselblad X2D 100C, 85mm f/1.4, ISO 100, RAW — hyperrealistic editorial photography —
8K resolution — cinematic depth of field — professional commercial lighting — no distortion —
anatomically correct — skin texture visible — photojournalistic realism
```

**Seed Strategy:**
- Always document the seed used
- Suggest seed variants (+1, +7, +13) for subtle exploration
- Suggest temperature variants (±0.1) for mood shifts
- Suggest top_p variants (0.95 vs 0.99) for diversity range

